            / Introduction
            .mb-8
              p.text-lg.text-gray-700.mb-6
                | From the very beginning, we wanted to make adding interactivity as simple as point and click.
              
              p.text-lg.text-gray-700.mb-6
                | That's why the Baldrick8 shipped with three inputs that could control not only other Baldrick boards, but also software like FPP.
              
              p.text-lg.text-gray-700.mb-6
                | We've seen people connect them to beam breaks and motion sensors, but by far the most popular use has been with buttons. Pretty quickly, the requests rolled in for a way to control the button lamp too â€” for example, turning it off when the button couldn't be pressed.
              
              p.text-lg.text-gray-700.mb-6
                | That led us to create the BaldrickInput1, a standalone controller dedicated to interactivity, with lamp control built in and improved Turnip Network integration.
              
              p.text-lg.text-gray-700.mb-6
                | And from there, an Input fully powered by the Turnip Network was born: the 
                strong Turniput
                | .
              
              p.text-lg.text-gray-700.mb-8
                | Now standard across all new boards the Turniput allows easy interaction without any scripting or code.

